weapons.name: MG 42
weapons.description: This ground-breaking machine gun was reliable, easy to use, and had an extreme rate of fire. Due to the sound made by the high firing rate, the Allies nicknamed the MG42 "Hitler's Buzzsaw". The MG42 saw action on all fronts.

weapons.name: MG 34
weapons.description: The MG34 was the first of a kind: a portable, air-cooled machine gun with a high rate of fire. Too complex to properly mass-produce, it was later supplanted by the MG42.

weapons.name: VGO
weapons.description: The VGO began life as an airplane-mounted machine gun. But it was soon adopted for land use. A high rate of fire made it a favorite among Allied commando units.

weapons.name: M1922 MG
weapons.description: The French never got to field their M1922 light machine gun during World War I. Many variants lived on into World War II however, where they were mainly used in the French Navy.

weapons.name: S2-200
weapons.description: The S2-200 was a magazine-fed machine gun originally banned by the Treaty of Versailles after World War I. Rejected by the German infantry, the Luftwaffe eventually adopted them for use in their aircraft.

weapons.name: M1919A6
weapons.description: The M1919 is mainly known as the .30 cal. machine gun. A bipod and a carrying handle was added which resulted in the A6 model.

weapons.name: Gewehr 43
weapons.description: This rifle is so sturdy it can be used as a ladder rung if needed. The Germans designed it when they saw that the Red Army had adopted semi-automatic rifles.

weapons.name: M1A1 Carbine
weapons.description: The M1A1 was one of the most iconic weapons of World War II. US troops loved it due to its firepower, light weight and small size.

weapons.name: Turner SMLE
weapons.description: The Turner SMLE had many qualities, but simplicity was not one of them. It did well in extremely cold conditions and the Canadian Army tested it, but they didn't adopt it.

weapons.name: Selbstlader 1916
weapons.description: The Selbstlader 1916 was an early German semi-automatic rifle whose sensitivity to field conditions made it more popular with the German air force than its army. Only 1000 were ever made.

weapons.name: Gewehr 1-5
weapons.description: The German military created the Volksturmgewehr to arm the German civilians with as a last line of defense. It was a semi-automatic rifle and used the same detachable magazine as the StG 44.

weapons.name: Ag m/42
weapons.description: The Swedish army fielded a limited number of m/42 during World War II. Some rifles found their way to Norway immediately after the war, and it's possible that the m/42 was also used by resistance groups.

weapons.name: MAS 44
weapons.description: The MAS 44 was a French secret so well-kept from the German Army that it barely survived. Samples ended up in the hands of partisans. It didn't enter mass production until after the war.

weapons.name: Karabin 1938M
weapons.description: Influenced by the BAR, this Polish made rifle was in early troop trials as war broke out. A semi-automatic, fixed magazine rifle reminiscent of popular carbines that were already in use.

weapons.name: M1 Garand
weapons.description: A very reliable semi-automatic rifle that was standard issue for American infantry during the war. Probably best known for the en-bloc clip it utilizes, or rather the distinct sound it makes when the last round is fired.

weapons.name: M3 Infrared
weapons.description: Equipped with an infrared spotlight and scope this converted M1A1 Carbine was intended for night fighting. Although the enhanced optics were cutting edge technology, the added weight made the rifle cumbersome.

weapons.name: M1941 Johnson
weapons.description: A semi-automatic rifle that featured a rotating bolt and a cylindrical magazine. The reduced weight at the front of the rifle compared to other rifles at the time made easy handling. While never formally adopted by US forces, a number of them found their way into troops hands.

weapons.name: Scout Knife M1916
weapons.description: At the fall of France in 1940, the German infantry captured a large number of French knives which they later used in Norway. They had a wooden handle and double-edged blade.

weapons.name: Hatchet
weapons.description: A hatchet is not just for felling small trees or chopping fire wood. In the hands of a skilled soldier it becomes a terrible weapon in close combat, rightly feared by the enemy.

weapons.name: Club
weapons.description: Some soldiers carried clubs for use when the fighting got close and personal. These came in all sizes, as well as occasionally being armed with spikes to make them even more deadly.

weapons.name: Shovel
weapons.description: Any soldier worth his salt will tell you that a shovel is good for more than just digging. They are also effective weapons in close combat and some soldiers even took to sharpening the edges.

weapons.name: Pickaxe
weapons.description: While pickaxes were issued to British soldiers as a traditional tool, they were often used in unintended ways, including as a weapon and to scuttle vehicles to keep them from falling into enemy hands.

weapons.name: Kukri
weapons.description: The bent shape of the Nepalese kukri made it a particularly good knife for chopping. The elite soldiers of the British Gurkha regiment made these famous during World War II.

weapons.name: British Army Jack Knife
weapons.description: The jack knife was given to nearly every British soldier in World War II. It had a folding blade of about three inches, as well as a combined tin opener and screwdriver tool.

weapons.name: Coupe Coupe
weapons.description: Despite a resemblance to long bladed instruments, machetes are most commonly used as a hacking tool in line with an axe or a cleaver. Its sharpened cutting edge makes it as useful a weapon as it is for clearing undergrowth.

weapons.name: Lever Pipe
weapons.description: Improving on the practice of turning any heavy implement into a weapon, soldiers found that a pipe with the lever valve still attached gave it a weight and balance for a more impactful strike.

weapons.name: K98 Bayonet
weapons.description: The K98 Bayonet was the standard bayonet given to German soldiers during World War II. It was fitted for the Kar98 rifle and came with a wood or bakelite handle.

weapons.name: Poignard
weapons.description: This type of dagger was used for centuries. It was popular in France among other countries.

weapons.name: German Naval Dagger
weapons.description: This dagger was carried by German naval officers starting in the 1930s.

weapons.name: Broken Bottle
weapons.description: Improvised weapons were often a necessity during wartime. Bottles tended to be in abundance both in urban and rural situations, whether they were discovered or property of the soldiers.

weapons.name: Hachiwari
weapons.description: Designed as a multi purpose melee weapon, the hook-like protrusion was originally used to grab the cords of armor and helmets.

weapons.name: Escape Axe
weapons.description: Pilots were issued these axes to escape the fuselage of crashed planes if they did not manage to bail first. Incidentally they cut into flesh as well as they mangle a fuselage.

weapons.name: EGW Survival Knife
weapons.description: The EGW survival knife was never officially issued by the US Army, though soldiers often bought one for themselves. They were very versatile with a serrated back edge but were also prone to rust.

weapons.name: Combat Knife
weapons.description: A combat and utility knife designed as much as a tool as it is a weapon.

weapons.name: Commando Machete
weapons.description: While its shape suggests that it should be used to clear branches in the jungle, the reduced weight of this machete makes it nimble enough to be used as a quick slashing weapon as well.

weapons.name: Sai
weapons.description: While its appearance is intimidating, generally the points are blunted rather than sharp. This increased the utility of the design by allowing the weapon to be manipulated into various positions without the danger of harming oneself.

weapons.name: Bolo-Guna
weapons.description: This Filipino agricultural tool may have been more likely found in a garden than on a battlefield, but its usefulness was just as remarkable in both theaters.

weapons.name: Knuckle Duster
weapons.description: Many ideas were experimented with during the first Great War regarding close quarters combat. This design was the result of an attempt to have as many offensive options as possible

weapons.name: Ilse's Pickaxe
weapons.description: Decorated with a sword portepee strap normally found on dress uniform swords. No one is sure of its significance to Ilse, but the axe has likely seen more use than most.

weapons.name: Control Stick
weapons.description: Although once capable of controlling a mighty machine, it now serves another purpose.

weapons.name: Lion Head Sword
weapons.description: An ornamental sword created before the war and given to Siegfrieds father that was then handed down to him. Its construction and fine details are of remarkable quality.

weapons.name: Golden Eagle
weapons.description: A well worn blade adorned with a brass pommel sculpted into an eagle head. It has been passed  on to several members of the demolition section as a sign of respect and thanks.

weapons.name: Boys AT Rifle
weapons.description: A British anti-tank rifle. Proving ineffective against improved axis tanks, it was replaced by the PIAT during the war.

weapons.name: Panzerbchse 39
weapons.description: Compared to most anti-tank rifles, the Panzerbchse 39 fires a very light projectile at very high velocity, relying on speed rather than mass to penetrate armor.

weapons.name: Frag Grenade Rifle
weapons.description: Long range grenade launcher based on the SMLE carbine, effective against infantry. The launched projectiles explode on impact.

weapons.name: Sticky Dynamite
weapons.description: Sticky bundle of dynamite that can be placed and detonated on demand. Effective against structures, vehicles and infantry.

weapons.name: Panzerfaust
weapons.description: The Panzerfaust is a disposable launch tube firing a shaped charge Anti-Tank warhead.

weapons.name: Ammo Crate
weapons.description: Ammo Crates provides a fixed supply position allowing for re-supplying weapons and gadgets.

weapons.name: Bandages
weapons.description: Single-use field dressings that heal a single soldier on the move. Any damage will cancel the heal.

weapons.name: AT Mine
weapons.description: Anti-Tank Mines will explode and cause significant damage when traversed by enemy vehicles.

weapons.name: AP Mine
weapons.description: The Schrapnellmine or ''Bouncing Betty'' is a tripwire anti-personnel mine. When triggered, it bounces up and deploys a lethal spray of shrapnel that can only be avoided by quickly going prone.

weapons.name: Medical Crate
weapons.description: A Medical Crate will provide a fixed healing position for a squad to regroup, defend or prepare a coordinated assault.

weapons.name: Spotting Scope
weapons.description: Spot enemies and share their positions with your teammates.

weapons.name: Flare Gun
weapons.description: The Flare Gun shoots a high altitude spotting flare projectile which reveals enemies on a large area.

weapons.name: Spawn Beacon
weapons.description: Place this radio on the field to allow your Squad mates to come into reinforcement.

weapons.name: Smoke Grenade
weapons.description: Smoke grenades will provide a smoke barrage preventing a clear line of sight.

weapons.name: Frag Grenade
weapons.description: Standard No. 36M MkI timed fuze hand grenade inflicting high damage to soldiers.

weapons.name: Incendiary Grenade
weapons.description: Incendiary hand grenade which creates intense flames for a short duration. Flames stick to soldiers and will continue to burn outside the original fire.

weapons.name: PIAT
weapons.description: The PIAT is a rocket launcher, effective against both Infantry and armored vehicles. Handle with care.

weapons.name: AT Grenade Pistol
weapons.description: The Sturmpistole fires Anti-Tank shaped charges indirectly at long distances.

weapons.name: Smoke Grenade Rifle
weapons.description: Long range smoke grenade launcher based on the SMLE carbine, effective at blocking the enemy view.

weapons.name: Anti-Tank Bundle Grenade
weapons.description: M24 Geballte Ladung. This bundle of grenades will detonate upon contact with a vehicle to deal significant damage.

weapons.name: Sticky Grenade
weapons.description: A lighter, but sticky anti tank grenade. Effective against armored vehicles.

weapons.name: Throwing Blade
weapons.description: A sharp and well balanced blade to silently take down an enemy from a distance.

weapons.name: Impact Grenade
weapons.description: No. 69 Impact is a grenade which detonates almost immediately upon impact.

weapons.name: Medical Syringe
weapons.description: An adrenaline injection that can be used to revive downed allies.

weapons.name: Fliegerfaust
weapons.description: A German prototype man-portable anti-aircraft launcher. Fires two salvos of unguided rockets.

weapons.name: Shaped Charge
weapons.description: A magnetic explosive charge that can be attached to vehicles. Detonated by time fuze.

weapons.name: Lunge Mine
weapons.description: An extraordinarily high risk anti-tank weapon consisting of a shaped charge at the end of a stick. While it most likely damaged enemy armor it absolutely harmed the operator when it was used correctly.

weapons.name: M1A1 Bazooka
weapons.description: The M1A1 Bazooka launches an anti tank rocket with high acceleration and long effective range. Users need to be careful of the back blast which can injure personnel and detonate munitions directly behind the shooter.

weapons.name: M2 Flamethrower
weapons.description: After entering the war, the U.S. quickly saw a need for developing a flamethrower for infantry use. The end result was a cutting edge design that was extremely reliable and safe, for the user.

weapons.name: Katana
weapons.description: Many swords were produced in the years leading up to the war as Japanese officers were required to wear them. The quality varied dramatically due to the amount that was needed in the short period of time.

weapons.name: Kunai
weapons.description: Most likely derived from a masonry or gardening tool and transformed into a formidable and silent throwing weapon.

weapons.name: Doppel-Schuss
weapons.description: Adopted by German naval crews as they rose to prominence early in the war. Used to signal and illuminate where no other lights were available, in the middle of the sea.

weapons.name: Type 99 Mine
weapons.description: A light, thrown, anti-tank mine that sticks only to vehicles and explodes on a timer between 5-10 seconds. Two of these light mines are carried at once.

weapons.name: Firecrackers
weapons.description: Used to similate the sounds of gunfire to confuse the enemy and their information systems.

weapons.name: RMN50 Rifle Frag
weapons.description: More hand mortar then grenade launcher, the RMN50 fires standard 50mm mortar shells from a converted Mosin-Nagant that will explode after a timer, even in midair.

weapons.name: Demolition Grenade
weapons.description: The No.75 Hawkins grenade works as a low power anti-tank mine, and can be thrown a longer distance than a tranditional heavy anti-tank mine.

weapons.name: Pistol Flamethrower
weapons.description: A hand held, disposable, flamethrower firing a short burst of flame that can devastate individual infantry targets.

weapons.name: Kampfpistole
weapons.description: The Kampfpistole fires heavy Anti-Personal charges indirectly at medium and short distances.

weapons.name: Lewis Gun
weapons.description: The Lewis Gun entered Allied service in 1914. In World War II, the British again used it as an anti-aircraft gun. Its barrel shroud and top-mounted pan magazine made it easy to recognize.

weapons.name: KE7
weapons.description: Even though this light machine gun was designed in Switzerland, the Swiss army never used it. It had a quick-change barrel and a selective fire mode similar to that on many submachine guns.

weapons.name: Bren Gun
weapons.description: The British built this light machine gun based on a Czechoslovak design. It had a top-mounted magazine which gave it a distinct look. It was very popular with the troops.

weapons.name: FG-42
weapons.description: With its selective fire functionality the FG 42 was way ahead of its time. German paratroopers used and liked it, but it was never produced in great numbers.

weapons.name: LS/26
weapons.description: A Finnish light machine gun that saw use in the Winter and Continuation War against the Soviet Union.

weapons.name: Madsen MG
weapons.description: The Danish-made Madsen was introduced in 1902.  It was the first light machine gun in wide use. Like the Bren it had a top-mounted magazine, and were the standard LMG issued by the Norwegian army.

weapons.name: Chauchat
weapons.description: In World War I, the standard French light machine gun was called the Chauchat. It could be handled by a crew of just two, which was rare at the time. It had many features seen on later LMGs.

weapons.name: BAR M1918A2
weapons.description: An updated version of an automatic rifle that was developed during the Great War. The new version made reloading easier and could be used with a bipod.

weapons.name: Type 97 MG
weapons.description: A machine gun based upon a Czech design, modified for use in Japanese tanks. It was less commonly used as an infantry weapon due to the excessive weight.

weapons.name: Type 11 LMG
weapons.description: This early Japanese machine gun design included a unique offset hopper feed system that utilized the same cartridge clips as some of the Japanese infantry rifles simplifying ammunition logistics on the battlefield.

weapons.name: 12g Automatic
weapons.description: The 12g Automatic served in both world wars. It was the first successful semi-automatic shotgun used by the Allies, eventually inspiring the German army to create their own version.

weapons.name: M30 Drilling
weapons.description: In case Luftwaffe pilots got shot down, they had this weapon to both hunt game and protect themselves with. The M30 had two shotgun barrels and one normal rifle barrel.

weapons.name: M1897
weapons.description: The US-made M1897 is most famously known as the "Trench Gun". More than one million were built. It was used by soldiers, policemen and hunters around the world.

weapons.name: Model 37
weapons.description: Pump action shotguns remained popular since their debut in the late 19th century. While the design of this shotgun was kept simple its reliability and effectiveness in combat was renowned.

weapons.name: Sjgren Shotgun
weapons.description: While its inertia-based loading system proved to be ahead of its time, the Sjgren's service in World War II was mostly centered around different resistance groups.

weapons.name: Trench Carbine
weapons.description: Built as a prototype to fulfill a request from the German army. Although its design was based on other popular pistols used during the Great War, the Trench Carbine is unique in many ways.

weapons.name: P08 Carbine
weapons.description: Based on the P08 Pistol, this carbine variant has a stock, extended barrel and snail magazine offering improved ranged performance.

weapons.name: Liberator
weapons.description: The Americans created the Liberator pistol for use by resistance groups. Simple to manufacture, it was known for its single-shot functionality. The Allies gave large numbers to the French resistance.

weapons.name: Repetierpistole M1912
weapons.description: The M1912 was a rugged and dependable pistol with an integral magazine. First used in World War I, the German Army ordered 60,000 pistols when Germany annexed Austria in 1938.

weapons.name: Mk VI Revolver
weapons.description: The Mk VI was the standard revolver for the British army in both World War I and World War II. The earliest version, the Mk I, was the first put into service by the army in 1887.

weapons.name: M1911
weapons.description: When people think of a .45, they often imagine the M1911 automatic pistol. They were so popular in World War II that several gun manufacturers were needed to meet the demand.

weapons.name: P38 Pistol
weapons.description: The P38 pistol was the standard German sidearm in World War II. Some of its technical solutions are still in use today. It was chambered for the 9mm Parabellum round.

weapons.name: Ruby
weapons.description: The Ruby pistol was incredibly easy to use, which was why it survived long after World War II. It first saw action in World War I where it was a great back-up weapon in trench warfare.

weapons.name: P08 Pistol
weapons.description: The P08 pistol is commonly known as the "Luger", named after the man who patented it. The German military tried replacing it with the P38 during World War II, but it would remain in production until 1943.

weapons.name: Type 94
weapons.description: Manufactured in Japan since before the war, some viewed this pistol as being unnecessarily complex in its design while others admired that it was compact and lightweight.

weapons.name: Model 27
weapons.description: Utilized by several law enforcement agencies in the United States before the war it remained popular due to its renowned reliability and effectiveness at longer ranges than other pistols.

weapons.name: Welrod
weapons.description: The British developed the Welrod pistol to be as quiet as possible. It was bolt-operated and magazine fed. At only 73 dBA, it was about as loud as a present-day car.

weapons.name: PPK
weapons.description: Designed in 1929, the PPK is the short version of the PP.  While the newer P38 was the standard sidearm of German military during World War II the PPK was adopted in small numbers throughout the war.

weapons.name: PPKS
weapons.description: Designed in 1929, the PPK is the short version of the PP.  While the newer P38 was the standard sidearm of German military during World War II the PPK was adopted in small numbers throughout the war.

weapons.name: M1911 Suppressed
weapons.description: When people think of a .45, they often imagine the M1911 automatic pistol. They were so popular in World War II that several gun manufacturers were needed to meet the demand.

weapons.name: StG 44
weapons.description: Many consider the Sturmgewehr 44 to be the first real assault rifle. It combined a high rate of fire with high accuracy and stopping power. Several modern weapons are based on its design.

weapons.name: Sturmgewehr 1-5
weapons.description: The Sturmgewehr 1-5 was the selective-fire variant of the Gewehr 1-5 semi-automatic rifle. As the concept of a fully automatic 1-5 was ultimately rejected, very few were produced.

weapons.name: M1907 SF
weapons.description: The M1907 SF was similar to the M1 carbine, only heavier and more powerful. Some versions were modified so that they could fire on full auto. It was mainly used by the French and the British.

weapons.name: Breda M1935 PG
weapons.description: The first burst assault rifle of the era. Fires an accurate and deadly 4-round burst.

weapons.name: M2 Carbine
weapons.description: After the success of the M1 carbine this select fire version was developed that would allow fully automatic fire. The design was intended to deliver a similar firepower capability to the German fully automatic rifles in use at the time.

weapons.name: Commando Carbine
weapons.description: Despite its French-sounding name, the De Lisle carbine was a British weapon. It had an integrated suppressor, which was combined with subsonic ammo to make it one of the quietest firearms ever.

weapons.name: M28 con Tromboncino
weapons.description: A modernized M91 carbine that comes with a grenade launcher, useful both against infantry and vehicles.

weapons.name: Jungle Carbine
weapons.description: Formally called "Rifle No.5 Mk I", the No.5 Jungle Carbine is based on the Lee-Enfield No.4 Mk I.

weapons.name: M1928A1
weapons.description: The Chicago gangsters made the "Tommy Gun" famous in the 1920s. The US Army adopted it in 1938 for its accuracy and high rate of fire, and Allied Commando and Ranger units used it extensively.

weapons.name: MP34
weapons.description: The MP34's design was based on the old MP18 submachine gun. Used primarily by the German army, it was an extremely well-made gun although the production costs were very high.

weapons.name: MP28
weapons.description: After World War I, Hugo Schmeisser made many improvements to the MP18, such as replacing the drum magazine with a straight one. The resulting MP28 was sold to both China and Japan among others.

weapons.name: STEN
weapons.description: The famous Sten submachine gun was wildly popular with the British army during World War II. It compensated for its low accuracy with a high rate of fire. It was a cheap and simple design that proved easy to mass-produce.

weapons.name: Suomi KP/-31
weapons.description: The KP/-31 was possibly the best submachine gun of World War II. It had great accuracy and a high rate of fire. The Russians copied the design, but their version never reached the same high standard.

weapons.name: EMP
weapons.description: This submachine gun got around. The Germans built it and the Spaniards used it in the Spanish Civil War. Later both the French and the Germans deployed it.

weapons.name: MP40
weapons.description: The Germans used this gun in great numbers. The Allies called it the "Schmeisser", but the weapon designer Hugo Schmeisser was never involved in its design.

weapons.name: ZK-383
weapons.description: Firing pistol rounds, the German Army used the ZK-383 as a submachine gun despite it having many of the features found in a full-fledged machine gun, such as a detachable barrel and integrated bipod.

weapons.name: MAB 38
weapons.description: The MAB38 is a submachine gun used by the Italian military during World War 2. Other countries used it into the 1960s.

weapons.name: Type 100
weapons.description: Perhaps the only submachine gun manufactured within Japan in any significant quantity, it utilized a smaller caliber ammunition than most other SMGs of the time.

weapons.name: M3 Grease Gun
weapons.description: Light, cheap, and easy to manufacture were the goals when designing this submachine gun. The result ended up being an effective weapon for many years after its initial production.

weapons.name: Type 2A
weapons.description: An experimental submachine gun design put into production due to the urgent need of automatic firing infantry weapons.

weapons.name: Welgun
weapons.description: The Special Operations Executive had many projects going during the war. Among these was the Welgun, a submachine gun that would be easy to use and cheap to produce. Only a few prototypes were made.

weapons.name: KragJrgensen
weapons.description: The origins of the Danish Krag-Jrgensen rifle date back to the late 19th century. The gun's main feature was a special type of integral magazine which loaded from the side rather than the top.

weapons.name: Gewehr M95/30
weapons.description: The Gewehr M95/30's origins dated back to the late 19th century and saw heavy use in World War I by the Austro-Hungarian Army. By the WW II, the gun had mainly relegated to secondary militia units.

weapons.name: Lee-Enfield No.4 Mk I
weapons.description: The Lee Enfield rifle has a long history which goes back to before World War I. The no. 4 model had a brutal bayonet called the "pigsticker" by the British troops.

weapons.name: Kar98k
weapons.description: The Kar-98k was the most common bolt-action rifle in the German army. Millions were produced before and during World War II. Many of them are still in use today.

weapons.name: Ross Rifle Mk III
weapons.description: Although the Ross was exceptionally accurate, its length and sensitivity to poor ammunition made the rifle unsuitable for infantry use. It proved very popular with British and Canadian snipers though.

weapons.name: Type 99 Arisaka
weapons.description: Equipped with a shorter barrel than most sniper rifles manufactured during the war, a choice that saved cost and materials and was found to only have a nominal impact on its accuracy.

weapons.name: K31/43
weapons.description: The sniper variant of the Swiss K31 service rifle, the K31/43 has an integral periscopic scope.

weapons.name: RSC
weapons.description: By repurposing parts from the Lebel rifle it was designed to replace, the RSC was cheaper to produce for the French army, though there were complaints that it was unwieldy in the trenches.

weapons.name: Selbstlader 1906
weapons.description: The same toggle-lock mechanism used on the German P 08 pistol was also used for a semi-automatic rifle. The design was a success but only a few prototypes were ever built.

weapons.name: Model 8
weapons.description: The first successful American-made semi-auto rifle, the Model 8 shares the same long recoil mechanism as the Automatic 5 shotgun.

weapons.name: ZH-29
weapons.description: This was one of the first successful semi-automatic rifles and its design would go on to inspire the StG-44. The Chinese used it during World War II, but it was developed in Czechoslovakia.
